China Stocks: Anhui Conch, Southwest Securities, Wuliangye Yibin

-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 
2011-08-16T07:57:10Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-15/anhui-conch-china-life-wuliangye-yibin-china-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in  China  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 3 p.m. local time.  The Shanghai Composite Index, which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, fell 0.7 percent to 2,608.17. The  CSI
300 Index (SHSZ300)  lost 0.7 percent to 2,897.58.  Anhui Conch Cement Co. (600585 CH), the nation’s largest
cement producer, advanced 1.1 percent to 25.76 yuan, the highest
since Aug. 5. The company’s first-half net income rose 234
percent from the same period a year ago to 6 billion yuan ($939
million), according to a statement to the Shanghai Stock
Exchange.  CSR Corp. (601766 CH), the biggest train maker, rose 1.1
percent to 5.49 yuan, the highest since Aug. 4. Chairman Zhao
Xiaogang, Vice Chairman Zheng Changhong and 10 other CSR
officials bought a combined 544,100 Shanghai-listed shares for
as much as 5.46 yuan apiece after the train maker fell 20
percent in less than three weeks, according to a company
statement.  Sanan Optoelectronics Co. (600703 CH) jumped 4.3 percent to
15.39 yuan, the most since July 7. Net income surged 127 percent
to 459 million yuan in the first half, according to a statement
to the  Shanghai Stock Exchange .  Southwest Securities Co. (600369 CH) added 1.4 percent to
12.04 yuan, its highest close since Dec. 27. The company will
acquire closely held Guodu Securities Co. in a stock swap. Guodu
is valued at 11.3 billion yuan, Southwest said, according to a
statement to the Shanghai Stock Exchange. The stock last traded
on Feb. 28.  Wuliangye Yibin Co. (000858 CH) gained 1.2 percent to 39.65
yuan. The company’s net income increased 49 percent to 3.36
billion yuan in the first half, according to a statement to the
Shenzhen Stock Exchange.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at 
 dboey@bloomberg.net  